AllLife Credit Card Customer Segmentation¶

Background: AllLife Bank wants to focus on its credit card customer base in the next financial year. They have been advised by their marketing research team, that the penetration in the market can be improved. Based on this input, the Marketing team proposes to run personalised campaigns to target new customers as well as upsell to existing customers. Another insight from the market research was that the customers perceive the support services of the bank poorly. Based on this, the Operations team wants to upgrade the service delivery model, to ensure that customers queries are resolved faster. Head of Marketing and Head of Delivery both decide to reach out to the Data Science team for help.

Objective: To identify different segments in the existing customer based on their spending patterns as well as past interaction with the bank.

Key Questions:

  1. How many different segments of customers are there?
  2. How are these segments different from each other?
  3. What are your recommendations to the bank on how to better market to and service these customers?

Data Description: Data is of various customers of a bank with their credit limit, the total number of credit cards the customer has, and different channels through which customer has contacted the bank for any queries, different channels include visiting the bank, online and through a call centre.

Univariate analysis¶

In [8]:
# Function that will create boxplot and histogram for any input numerical variable.
# This function takes the numerical column as the input and returns the boxplots and histograms for the variable.
def histogram_boxplot(feature, figsize=(15,7), bins = None):
    """ Boxplot and histogram combined
    feature: 1-d feature array
    figsize: size of fig (default (15,7))
    bins: number of bins (default None / auto)
    """
    f2, (ax_box2, ax_hist2) = plt.subplots(nrows = 2, # Number of rows of the subplot grid= 2
                                           sharex = True, # x-axis will be shared among all subplots
                                           gridspec_kw = {"height_ratios": (.25, .75)}, 
                                           figsize = figsize 
                                           ) # creating the 2 subplots
    sns.boxplot(x=feature, data=df, ax=ax_box2, showmeans=True, color='violet') # boxplot will be created and a star will indicate the mean value of the column
    sns.histplot(x=feature, data=df, kde=False, ax=ax_hist2, bins=bins,palette="winter") if bins else sns.histplot(x=feature, data=df, kde=False, ax=ax_hist2) # For histogram
    ax_hist2.axvline(df[feature].mean(), color='green', linestyle='--') # Add mean to the histogram
    ax_hist2.axvline(df[feature].median(), color='black', linestyle='-') # Add median to the histogram

Elbow method¶

In [20]:
clusters=range(1,11)
meanDistortions=[]

for k in clusters:
    model=KMeans(n_clusters=k)
    model.fit(subset_scaled_df)
    prediction=model.predict(subset_scaled_df)
    distortion=sum(np.min(cdist(subset_scaled_df, model.cluster_centers_, 'euclidean'), axis=1)) / subset_scaled_df.shape[0]
                           
    meanDistortions.append(distortion)

    print('Number of Clusters:', k, '\tAverage Distortion:', distortion)

plt.plot(clusters, meanDistortions, 'bx-');
plt.xlabel('k')
plt.ylabel('Average Distortion')
plt.title('Selecting k with the Elbow Method', fontsize=20)

Hierarchical Clustering¶

Distance metrics and linkage methods¶

In [27]:
# The cophenetic correlation index is a measure of the correlation between the distance of points in feature space and 
# distance on dendrogram. The closer it is to 1, the better is the clustering
distance_metrics = ['euclidean','chebyshev','mahalanobis','cityblock']
linkage_methods = ['single', 'complete', 'average', 'weighted']
high_cophenet_corr = 0
high_dm_lm = [0,0]
for dm in distance_metrics:
    for lm in linkage_methods:
        Z = linkage(subset_scaled_df, metric=dm, method=lm)
        c, coph_dists = cophenet(Z , pdist(subset_scaled_df))
        print('Cophenetic correlation for distance metrics {} and linkage method {} is {:.3f}'.format(dm,lm,c))
        if high_cophenet_corr < c:
            high_cophenet_corr = c
            high_dm_lm[0] = dm
            high_dm_lm[1] = lm

Dendograms for different linkage methods¶

In [31]:
# List of all linkage methods to check
methods = ['single',
           'average', 
           'complete',
           'centroid',
           'ward',
          'weighted']

# Calculate the pairwise distance form the dataset to be used in the cophenetic correlation calculation
#pw_distance = pdist(credit_scaled)

# Create a subplot image
fig, axs = plt.subplots(len(methods), 1, figsize=(15, 30))

# Enumerate through the list of all methods above
# Get linkage, plot dendrogram, calculate cophenetic coefficient
for i, method in enumerate(methods):
    
    Z = linkage(subset_scaled_df, metric='euclidean', method=method)

    dendrogram(Z, 
               truncate_mode='lastp',  # show only the last p merged clusters
               p=40,  # show only the last p merged clusters
               ax=axs[i]);
    axs[i].set_title(f'Dendrogram ({method.capitalize()} Linkage)')
    coph_corr, coph_dist = cophenet(Z, pdist(subset_scaled_df))
    axs[i].annotate(f'Cophenetic\nCoefficient\n{coph_corr:0.3f}', 
                    (0.80, 0.80),
                    xycoords='axes fraction')
    compare.append([method, coph_corr])

Calculate average silhouette score for both clustering methods.¶

In [43]:
sil_score_Kmeans = []
sil_score_Hierar = []
cluster_list = list(range(2,11))
for n in cluster_list:
    
    kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters=n)
    pred_kmeans = kmeans.fit_predict((subset_scaled_df))
    kmean_score = silhouette_score(subset_scaled_df, pred_kmeans)
    sil_score_Kmeans.append(kmean_score)
    
    pred_hierar = fcluster(Z, t=n, criterion='maxclust')
    hierar_score = silhouette_score(subset_scaled_df, pred_hierar)
    sil_score_Hierar.append(hierar_score)
In [45]:
plt.plot(cluster_list,sil_score_Kmeans, label='Kmeans', color='r')
plt.plot(cluster_list,sil_score_Hierar, label='Hierarchical clustering', color='b')
plt.xlabel('Number of clusters')
plt.ylabel('Silhouette score')
plt.legend()
plt.show()

Slihouette plots¶

K-means with 3 clusters¶

In [51]:
#Silhouette plot for K-means with 3 clusters
plt.figure(figsize=(15,6))
cluster_labels = df_Kmean['K_means_segments']
silhouette_avg = silhouette_score(subset_scaled_df, cluster_labels)
sample_silhouette_values = silhouette_samples(subset_scaled_df, cluster_labels)
y_lower = 10
for i in range(1,4):
    # Aggregate the silhouette scores for samples belonging to
    # cluster i, and sort them
    ith_cluster_silhouette_values = \
    sample_silhouette_values[cluster_labels == i]
    ith_cluster_silhouette_values.sort()

    size_cluster_i = ith_cluster_silhouette_values.shape[0]
    y_upper = y_lower + size_cluster_i

    color = cm.nipy_spectral(float(i) / 3)
    plt.fill_betweenx(np.arange(y_lower, y_upper),
                          0, ith_cluster_silhouette_values,
                          facecolor=color, edgecolor=color, alpha=0.7)

    # Label the silhouette plots with their cluster numbers at the middle
    plt.text(-0.05, y_lower + 0.5 * size_cluster_i, str(i))

    # Compute the new y_lower for next plot
    y_lower = y_upper + 10  # 10 for the 0 samples

plt.title("The silhouette plot for K-means with 3 clusters.", {'fontsize': 15})
plt.xlabel("The silhouette coefficient values")
plt.ylabel("Cluster label")

# The vertical line for average silhouette score of all the values
plt.axvline(x=silhouette_avg, color="red", linestyle="--")

plt.yticks([])  # Clear the yaxis labels / ticks
plt.xticks(np.arange(-0.1,0.9,0.1))
plt.show()

Conclusion and Business Recommendations¶

These 660 customers can be split into 2 or 3 categories depending on the clustering method (K-means or hierarchical clustering).

  • Cluster 1 (223 customers) consists of customers with a low credit limit (12,174 on average). These customers have less credit cards and but call the bank very frequently. They are the less profitable customers for the bank at the moment. These customers should be incentivized to buy additional credit card services through customized marketing policies.
  • Cluster 3 (50 customers) consists of customers with a high credit limit (141,040 on average). These customers have many credit cards, do not visit or call the bank frequently and use online services. They are the most valuable customers for the bank.
  • Compared to cluster 1 and 3, cluster 2 (387 customers) represents a kind of intermediate category. If we were to choose only 2 clusters, this cluster would be merged with cluster 1. These customers have a medium credit limit (33,713 on average). They distinguish from the other groups of customers based on the high number of visits to the bank and low internet banking usage. This group of customer would perhaps benefit from staff guidance in order to become more familiar with the internet banking system.
